The axiid shrimp genus 

Eiconaxius
Bate, 1888

is currently represented by 37 species worldwide, all confined to deep sea; as far as known, many species are associated with farreid sponges (

; de Man 1925; 

; 

; 

, 2018, 2020; 

; 

; DecaNet 2024). Taxonomic problems relating to the genus, mostly brought by 

, have been clarified by 

. Several earlier described species have been redescribed or reevaluated recently (

; 

, 2018, 2020; 

). 

performed genetic analyses using two mitochondrial genes (16S rRNA and COI genes) for species of 

Eiconaxius

, showing genetic divergences for assessment of species status. From Japanese waters, the following four species are known: 

E. acutifrons
Bate, 1888

, 

E. farreae
Ortmann, 1891

, 

E. kumejimaensis
Sakai, 2014

, and 

E. mortenseni
Sakai, 1992

(

; de Man 1925; 

, 

; 

; 

). Of them 

E. farreae

and 

E. mortenseni

were originally described from Sagami Bay, central 
Japan
(

; 

).

Genomic DNA extraction, amplification of the 16S rRNA and COI genes, and sequencing followed 

. The obtained raw DNA sequences were assembled and edited by GENETYX-MAC v. 17 (Genetyx, 
Tokyo
, 
Japan
). The newly generated sequences were subjected to BLAST (Basic Local Alignment Search Tool, National Center for Biotechnology Information, NCBI) search against GenBank to check for potential contamination and find similar sequences in the database. The 16S rRNA and COI gene sequences from congeners in the GenBank were referred for DNA analyses (cf. 

), as summarised in 
Table 1
. Target sequences were aligned by MUSTLE (

) implemented in MEGA 11 (

). Pairwise distances based on the Kimura 2-parameter model (K2P divergence) were calculated by MEGA 11 to compare the divergences amongst the nominated species for evaluating the validity of the taxa under consideration.

